[3] Recent outbreak: impact upon sheep industry
Date: Wed 19 Sep 2007
Source: The Times online [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2485391.ece>

A new outbreak of FMD has been confirmed in cattle at the Krondyke Farm in
Virginia Water, Surrey, where sheep were slaughtered on suspicion of
infection on Monday night [17 Sep 2007].
It also emerged that a cow was moved from the 20-acre (8-hectare) farm last
Tuesday [11 Sep 2007] for slaughter at a Welsh abattoir. The farm, above,
has been owned by the [same] family for 100 years. The news immediately
fuelled concerns among farmers in Wales who fear that the disease will have
spread across their borders.
Government vets traced the beef carcass to the St Merryn Meat Company
premises in Merthyr Tydfil and it has been removed from the food chain for
testing. No disease has been found and there are no suspect animals on the
premises.
Debby Reynolds, the Government's chief veterinary officer, said yesterday
[18 Sep 2007] that vaccination would not be used to control the FMD
outbreak in Surrey while the risk of spread to other parts of the country
remained low.
Teams remain on standby near Guildford in case there is any evidence that
the disease has spread outside the protection zone or is widespread in a
particular species.
[byline: Valerie Elliott]
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the location of the Krondyke farm in Virginia Water, as well as the
other recently infected farms, see the excellent BBC map at
