[4] Resuming export: prospects and timetable
Date: Wed 19 Sep 2007
Source: The Scotsman [edited]
<http://business.scotsman.com/agriculture.cfm?id=1498312007>

The resumption of exports of beef and lamb is seen as a key element in
restoring financial viability to farming, but the situation is not quite as
simple as some producers may believe. Stuart Ashworth of Quality Meat
Scotland, the red meat promotional agency, has prepared a background paper
that details the complex nature of the livestock and processing sectors.
He said: "Export markets are more important to the sheep sector, at 25 per
cent of production, compared with the beef industry, where only 3 per cent
of the output is exported. However, trade patterns result in an estimated
33 per cent of Scottish beef and 10 per cent of lamb consumption being
imported."
There have been repeated calls over the past week for Scotland to adopt a
regional approach to winding down the restrictions imposed because of
foot-and-mouth disease. But trade within the UK is complex -- Ashworth
points out that up to a fifth of the beef and lamb "imported" into Scotland
may have originated north of the Border, before passing through
intermediaries in England and Wales.
In normal times a large number of Scottish lambs are delivered each week to
abattoirs as far south as Kent and Wales, but the principal processing
locations are in Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Cheshire. If Scotland was to
regionalise, there could be problems in returning that lamb for sale in
supermarkets before England is clear of the disease. The situation with
beef is similar.
The pig sector is feeling the pain most acutely; high feed costs and the
loss of export markets are placing producers under extreme pressure.
Ashworth said: "Around 5000 tonnes of pig meat from Scotland is exported
outwith [out of. - CopyEd.MJ] the UK each year, predominately made up of
heads, feet, and offals. This trade is worth about BP 3 [USD 6] per pig,
but with no UK market for these products, disposal costs are also around BP
3 per pig. This means that the loss of export markets costs BP 6 per pig
[USD 12], or potentially over BP 4 million [USD 8 million] in a full year
to the Scottish industry."
It is highly unlikely that exports from the UK will be permitted until late
October [2007] at the earliest. If Scotland goes alone it could be sooner,
but resuming the trade will not be without difficulties.
[byline: Dan Buglass]
--
communicated by:
FMD News, FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory
University of California at Davis
<fmdweb@ucdavis.edu>
<http://fmd.ucdavis.edu/index.php?id=maillist>
[The UK is a country which does not vaccinate against FMD and where
stamping out is applied. Such countries are, according to OIE's (Office
International des Epizooties; World Organisation for Animal Health) Code,
able to regain their freedom from FMD 3 months after the culling of the
last FMD case. In case of limited outbreaks, earlier resumption of exports
from uninfected areas has become possible since the OIE adoption of the
Containment zone principles. The terms for the establishment of a
containment zone, securing its recognition by trade partners, are spelled
out in article 2.2.10.7 of the Code. For details see commentary in
ProMED-mail post 20070917.3088. - Mod.AS]
